"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130711","Department for Transport","false","2019-06-12","<p>The table below shows the number of lorry or bus driving licence applications that have been refused or revoked for medical reasons over the last 10 years. However, not all these applications will have been supported by a D4 medical examination report.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Group 2 licence applications </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>Not held</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>4,583</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>5,539</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>6,122</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>7,464</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>7,494</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>8,095</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>10,665</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>11,213</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018</p></td><td><p>12,242</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2019 (until the end of May)</p></td><td><p>4,639</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130711/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-12T11:06:56.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130711/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130711/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-06-07","Driving: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many D4 medical examination applications have been refused during (a) each of the five years prior to December 2014 and (b) each year since December 2014.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","261518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130712","Department for Transport","false","2019-06-12","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) does not license centres or doctors to complete D4 medical examination reports. The D4 medical examination and report must be conducted by a qualified medical practitioner who is registered with the General Medical Council and licensed to practice in the UK, or registered within the EU (if the form is completed outside the UK). The examining practitioner must carry out the examination in accordance with requirements outlined in DVLA guidance.</p><p> </p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130712/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-12T11:18:37.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130712/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130712/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-06-07","Driving: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many DVLA centres are licensed to complete D4 medical examination reports.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","261519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130713","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-06-12","<p>Legitimate rescue homes do incredible work rescuing and rehoming thousands of sick, abandoned and stray animals each year. I recognise that with the ban on commercial third party sales coming into force, stakeholders are concerned that disreputable dealers could reinvent themselves as rescues. We are actively exploring these issues with the rescue and rehoming sector.</p><p> </p><p>We need to be confident of the benefits and the impacts of any regulations placed on rescue and rehoming centres, particularly on some of the smaller rescues. We will consider proposals once we have fully consulted with the sector and understood the impact of any proposals.</p><p> </p><p>In the meantime, in order to prevent third-party sellers from presenting themselves as rehoming centres, we will work with the Canine and Feline Sector Group and local authorities to develop specific guidance to help distinguish between non-commercial rescue and rehoming centres, which are charities, and pet sellers which are businesses.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130713/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-12T09:47:46.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130713/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130713/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-06-07","Pets: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if will bring forward legislative proposals on animal re-homing before the ban on the third party selling of puppies and kittens comes into effect in April 2020.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","261545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130714","Department for Education","false","2019-06-13","<p>I refer the hon. Member for Stockton North to the answer I gave on 10 June 2019 to Question <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2019-06-04/259855" target="_blank">259855</a>.</p><p>Decisions about any further funding will be taken as part of the upcoming Spending Review.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130714/answer",,,,,"261507 ; 261508","2019-06-13T15:14:38.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130714/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130714/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-06-07","Breakfast Clubs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate he has made of the value for money of the national school breakfast programme.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","261506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130715","Department for Education","false","2019-06-13","<p>I refer the hon. Member for Stockton North to the answer I gave on 10 June 2019 to Question <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2019-06-04/259855" target="_blank">259855</a>.</p><p>Decisions about any further funding will be taken as part of the upcoming Spending Review.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130715/answer",,,,,"261506 ; 261508","2019-06-13T15:14:38.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130715/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130715/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-06-07","Breakfast Clubs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether his Department plans to extend the national school breakfast programme.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","261507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130716","Department for Education","false","2019-06-13","<p>I refer the hon. Member for Stockton North to the answer I gave on 10 June 2019 to Question <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2019-06-04/259855" target="_blank">259855</a>.</p><p>Decisions about any further funding will be taken as part of the upcoming Spending Review.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130716/answer",,,,,"261506 ; 261507","2019-06-13T15:14:38.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130716/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130716/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-06-07","Pupils: Food Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department is taking to lower the number of children at risk of starting the school day hungry.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","261508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130717","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-06-17","<p>This is a devolved matter and the information provided therefore relates to England only.</p><p> </p><p>On leaving the EU, the UK will have an independent trade policy and a new agriculture policy to replace the Common Agricultural Policy. As a result, the impact of the UK’s departure from the EU on rural communities will depend not just on the shape of a UK-EU trade agreement but also on the Government’s future trade and agriculture policies once we have left the EU.</p><p> </p><p>In England Defra is the lead department for rural affairs but issues relating to rural communities are the responsibility of departments across Government. The Government is undertaking a comprehensive and wide ranging programme of ongoing analysis in support of our preparations for leaving the EU.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130717/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-17T15:10:31.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130717/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130717/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-06-07","Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will publish his Department's plans for rural communities in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","261526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130718","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-06-13","<p>My Department is engaging with local authorities and the debt advice sector to improve council tax collection, and to ensure council tax debt collection practices are fair, efficient and compassionate to those in genuine hardship. Following those discussions, we intend to publish updated guidance on good collection practices, before considering the scope for further reforms.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130718/answer",,,,,"261539","2019-06-13T16:32:45.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130718/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130718/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-06-07","Council Tax: Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether he has plans to widen his Department’s review into council tax collection to include how local authorities collect council tax debt under The Council Tax (Administration and Enforcement) Regulations 1992.","false","Biography information for Bambos Charalambous","Enfield, Southgate","Bambos Charalambous","261538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130719","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-06-13","<p>My Department is engaging with local authorities and the debt advice sector to improve council tax collection, and to ensure council tax debt collection practices are fair, efficient and compassionate to those in genuine hardship. Following those discussions, we intend to publish updated guidance on good collection practices, before considering the scope for further reforms.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130719/answer",,,,,"261538","2019-06-13T16:32:45.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130719/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130719/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-06-07","Council Tax: Non-payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether he has plans to amend The Council Tax (Administration and Enforcement) Regulations 1992 to prevent people becoming liable for their full annual council tax bill after missing one payment.","false","Biography information for Bambos Charalambous","Enfield, Southgate","Bambos Charalambous","261539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130720","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-06-17","<p>​The Foreign and Commonwealth Office is committed to defending Freedom of Religion or Belief as a universal human right which should be enjoyed by everyone. The Government is deeply concerned about the severity of violations of Freedom of Religion or Belief in many parts of the world. In recent years we have seen reports of a particular rise in the persecution of Christians. The Foreign Secretary recently asked the Bishop of Truro to conduct an independent global review into the persecution of Christians. The review will provide recommendations on the additional practical steps the FCO can take to support persecuted Christians. The Bishop has now submitted his interim report; he will submit his final report in the Summer.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130720/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-17T15:33:05.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130720/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130720/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-06-07","Christianity: Oppression","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to help ensure the protection of Christians from persecution in (a) Africa, (b) the Middle East and (c) East Asia.","false","Biography information for Luke Hall","Thornbury and Yate","Luke Hall","261520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130721","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-06-17","<p>​The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) is committed to defending Freedom of Religion or Belief as a universal human right which should be enjoyed by everyone. Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon as the Prime Minister's Special Envoy on Freedom of Religion or Belief leads this work across Government and we regularly raise this issue with governments across the world, through our diplomatic network and at the Human Rights Council and the UN. The UK also funds and supports projects that promote respect for all people of different faiths and none.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130721/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-17T15:35:59.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130721/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130721/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-06-07","Christianity: Oppression","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to promote religious tolerance throughout the world.","false","Biography information for Luke Hall","Thornbury and Yate","Luke Hall","261521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130722","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-06-13","<p>It is the British Government's longstanding policy to oppose the death penalty in all circumstances and in all countries. In Pakistan, we remain deeply concerned by the misuse of blasphemy laws, and that religious minorities, including Christians, are disproportionately affected. The harsh penalties for blasphemy, including the death penalty, add to these concerns.</p><p>We regularly raise our human rights concerns with the Government of Pakistan at a senior level. My colleague, Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon, the Prime Minister's Special Envoy for Freedom of Religion or Belief, raised our concerns about Freedom of Religion or Belief and the protection of minority religious communities with Pakistan's Human Rights Minister in February 2019.</p><p>To ensure the United Kingdom is providing the right levels of support to persecuted Christians overseas, the Foreign Secretary asked the Bishop of Truro, Rt Revd. Philip Mounstephen, to carry out an independent review. The Bishop has submitted his interim report; with the full report due later this year.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130722/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-13T15:36:35.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130722/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130722/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-06-07","Pakistan: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to support Christians on death row in Pakistan on charges of blasphemy.","false","Biography information for Luke Hall","Thornbury and Yate","Luke Hall","261522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130723","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-06-17","<p>We have not made an assessment of the potential merits of establishing a fund for legal fees and access to justice. The Foreign Secretary has however launched the independent review of Foreign and Commonwealth Office support for persecuted Christians on 30 January. This review will provide robust recommendations on how the FCO can respond to the persecution of Christians when the final report is submitted in the Summer.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130723/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-17T15:39:43.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130723/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130723/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-06-07","Christianity: Oppression","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of establishing a fund to support persecuted Christians through help with legal fees and access to justice.","false","Biography information for Luke Hall","Thornbury and Yate","Luke Hall","261523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130724","Department for International Development","false","2019-06-14","<p>The UK Aid Strategy commits the UK to be the lead on the “Leave No One Behind” promise. Our analysis of poverty and vulnerability looks at a range of factors that lead to exclusion including religious identity. Humanitarian assistance is provided on need, irrespective of race, religion or ethnicity and we work to ensure that aid reaches the most vulnerable including those from religious minorities.</p><p> </p><p>We work closely with the Foreign and Commonwealth Office who lead on the protection of freedom of religion and religious minorities.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130724/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-14T13:40:13.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130724/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130724/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-06-07","Overseas Aid: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that UK aid reaches persecuted Christians.","false","Biography information for Luke Hall","Thornbury and Yate","Luke Hall","261524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130725","Department for International Development","false","2019-06-14","<p>All DFID partners carry out comprehensive vulnerability assessments to ensure aid is reaching those most in need, including those from religious minorities as it is already recognised that religion may be a factor in causing vulnerability. We continue to discuss the treatment of minorities with the UN, our humanitarian partners and minority representatives.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130725/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-14T13:41:33.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130725/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130725/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-06-07","Non-governmental Organisations: Religion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of requiring international NGOs to consider religious vulnerability in their definition of need.","false","Biography information for Luke Hall","Thornbury and Yate","Luke Hall","261525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130726","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-06-17","<p>Trees, woods and forests are a devolved matter and the information provided therefore relates to England only. Neither Defra nor the Forestry Commission records tree planting data except for trees planted in England with central government support.</p><p> </p><p>The latest figures from the Forestry Commission’s Corporate Plan Performance Indicators, published on 13 June, show that from April 2018 to March 2019 at least 2.06 million trees have been planted with central government support, equivalent to approximately 1,273 hectares of woodland creation.</p><p> </p><p>The Forestry Commissioners are responsible for the control of tree felling under the provisions in Part II of the Forestry Act 1967 (as amended). However, there are a number of exemptions from the requirements for a Felling Licence, including trees growing in private gardens, trees felled directly as a result of the granting of planning permission, felling approved in a legacy English Woodland Grant Scheme and trees felled on the Public Forest Estate. There is also no obligation to fell the trees once a Licence, which can be valid for up to 10 years, has been granted. These are some of the reasons why we do not know how many trees have been cut down. In the vast majority of cases where clear felling has been approved there will be a restocking requirement attached to the Licence.</p><p> </p><p>The Forestry Commission also publishes, as part of its Corporate Plan Performance Indicators, the net change in woodland area based on the balance between new planting of woodland and woodland removal, this information was last updated on 13 June 2019 and can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/forestry-commission-corporate-plan-performance-indicators" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/forestry-commission-corporate-plan-performance-indicators</a></p><p> </p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130726/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-17T15:00:58.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130726/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130726/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-06-07","Trees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many trees were (a) planted and (b) cut down in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","261476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130727","Department for International Development","false","2019-06-14","<p>The UK welcomes the recent UN-mediated talks between the Central Bank of Yemen Aden and Sana’a branches on enacting the revenue-managing elements of the Stockholm agreement. We recognise that closer collaboration between the branches of the Central Bank will be vital in bringing economic stability to Yemen.</p><p> </p><p>We encourage both parties to continue to constructively engage with Special Envoy Martin Griffiths and meet again to discuss this issue to ensure Stockholm agreements are implemented, helping improve Yemen’s fragile economy and ensure the payment of public sector salaries across the country.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130727/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-14T13:35:10.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130727/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130727/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-06-07","Central Bank of Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to recent UN-mediated talks in Amman between officials of Yemen’s Central bank what steps he is taking to support further such meetings.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","261473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130728","Department for International Development","false","2019-06-14","<p>The UK welcomes recent efforts by both parties to constructively engage with the UN Special Envoy Martin Griffiths to implement the Stockholm agreements, including sharing Hodeidah port revenues for the payment of public salaries.</p><p> </p><p>Together with the international community, the UK is working with the Government of Yemen’s Prime Minister’s Office and the Central Bank of Yemen to develop a plan to sustainably finance the Stockholm agreement’s ambition for the payment of public sector salaries across Yemen, through an accountable budgetary process.</p><p> </p><p>We welcome the Government of Yemen’s leadership of paying salaries to some health workers in Houthi-controlled areas and all public workers in Hodeidah this year. We encourage this to continue which will be vital in restoring key services such as schools and health clinics and boosting the livelihoods of public-sector workers.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130728/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-14T13:37:10.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130728/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130728/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-06-07","Central Bank of Yemen: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to the UN-mediated talks in Amman between officials in Yemen’s Central bank, what steps he is taking to ensure civil servants are paid as set out in the Stockholm Agreement.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","261474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130729","Department for International Development","false","2019-06-14","<p>The Department for International Development does not have insight into how Houthi revenue flows have changed over time. The UK condemns Houthi interference in the operations of local banks in north Yemen, including the arrest of banking staff in February 2019.</p><p> </p><p>Effective economic regulations, alongside appropriate economic policies, will have critical humanitarian benefits in Yemen. Whilst the latest total food import levels into Yemen have exceeded pre-conflict requirements, high prices continue to drive the risk of famine.</p><p> </p><p>The need for effective economic regulation was demonstrated last year, when the Yemeni Riyal lost more than half of its value between January and October 2018. This caused prices to rise steeply and risked making food unaffordable for millions of vulnerable Yemenis. This depreciation was reversed after UK-led efforts released over $400 million of hard currency (provided by Saudi Arabia), to importers bringing food into the country.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to constructively engage with the Government of Yemen to prevent any repeated depreciation, and to stabilise Yemen’s economy through more effective and transparent management of its public finance.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130729/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-14T13:39:06.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130729/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130729/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-06-07","Yemen: Financial Institutions and Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment he has made of the economic effect of regulating (a) imports, (b) commercial banks and (c) money exchangers in Yemen on Houthi revenues in that country.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","261475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130730","Department for International Development","false","2019-06-12","<p>The UK Government takes the issue of substandard and falsified medicines seriously and is committed to tackling malaria. Through DFID and the Department of Health and Social Care, we fund the WHO Global Surveillance and Monitoring System, which helps countries to identify and report substandard and falsified products, including anti-malaria medication in Africa.</p><p> </p><p>DFID also funds the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, TB and Malaria, which is committed to responsible and sustainable procurement and investigates any reported cases of substandard and falsified medicines through its Office of the Inspector General. We support countries to strengthen their health systems and work closely with partners to raise awareness on good distribution practices to minimise the risk of these medicines entering the supply chain. Our support to Product Development Partnerships for research and development for new products also includes anti-counterfeiting measures to reduce the risk of substandard and falsified medicines entering the supply chain, for example using labels or packaging that are difficult to copy.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130730/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-12T15:59:42.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130730/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130730/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-06-07","Africa: Malaria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps the Government is taking to help tackle counterfeit anti-malaria medication in Africa.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","261471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130731","Department for Transport","false","2019-06-12","<p>Six railway stations have been opened in the north of England since 2010:</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>2018:</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><ul><li>Maghull North</li></ul><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>2017</strong>:</p><ul><li>Low Moor</li></ul><p><strong>2016</strong>:</p><ul><li>Kirkstall Forge</li></ul><p><strong>2015</strong>:</p><ul><li>Apperley Bridge</li></ul><p><strong>2014</strong>:</p><ul><li>James Cook University Hospital</li></ul><p><strong>2011</strong>:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Buckshaw Parkway</li></ul><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Since 2010, no railway stations have closed in the north of England.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130731/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-12T14:21:15.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130731/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130731/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-06-07","Railway Stations: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 6 June 2019 to Question 259184, how many railway stations have been (a) opened and (b) closed in the north of England since 2010.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","261504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130732","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-06-12","<p>On 17 May 2019, we sent letters to all building owners eligible for the private sector remediation fund. We will continue to engage with building owners, managing agents, developers, local authorities and others to establish the fund.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130732/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-12T14:00:43.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130732/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130732/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-06-07","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, on what date his Department plans to write to building owners eligible for the aluminium composite material cladding fund.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","261509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130733","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-06-12","<p>The fund will include all high-rise (over 18 metres) residential private sector buildings with unsafe Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding, except where a warranty claim has been accepted.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130733/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-12T14:01:11.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130733/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130733/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-06-07","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what criteria his Department is using to determine whether building owners should be sent a letter regarding the aluminium composite material Cladding Fund.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","261510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130734","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-06-12","<p>I refer the Rt Hon Member to the written ministerial statement HCWS1533 made on 1 May 2019.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130734/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-12T14:01:34.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130734/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130734/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-06-07","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what the timescale is for (a) the testing regime for non-aluminium composite material cladding to be completed and (b) publishing the results from the testing regime for non-aluminium composite material cladding.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","261511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130735","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-06-12","<p>We are engaging with all relevant building owners to encourage swift applications. We are backing local authorities to take enforcement action where building owners are refusing to remediate high-rise buildings with unsafe cladding, including by establishing a Joint Inspection Team to support local authorities and give them the confidence to pursue enforcement action.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130735/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-12T14:02:15.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130735/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130735/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-06-07","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department plans to take in cases where building owners eligible for the aluminium composite material Cladding Fund do not apply within three months of being written to.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","261512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130736","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-06-17","<p>We have now written to all building owners eligible for the private sector remediation fund. We are not publishing details which could identify buildings because of the risk to public safety.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130736/answer",,,,,,"2019-06-17T16:46:39.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130736/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130736/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-06-07","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many letters his Department is planning to send regarding the ACM Cladding fund; and if he will publish the (a) names of the residential buildings and (b) constituencies in which those buildings are located that his Department is sending such letters to.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","261513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130737","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-06-12","<p>Information for the regions is not held in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>Once Armed Forces personnel have left the service, the provisions for their health and welfare support needs are primarily provided by the Department of Health and Social Care and the Department for Work and Pensions alongside the NHS in England and the Devolved Regions. Additional welfare support is also provided by the third sector in the form of Service charities and benevolent organisations. Some welfare support is provided by the Department through its Veteran UK organisation.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130737/answer",,,,,"261533","2019-06-12T15:36:28.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130737/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130737/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-06-07","Veterans: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of total spending on veterans' support services in each region of the UK in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","261532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130738","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-06-12","<p>Information for the regions is not held in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>Once Armed Forces personnel have left the service, the provisions for their health and welfare support needs are primarily provided by the Department of Health and Social Care and the Department for Work and Pensions alongside the NHS in England and the Devolved Regions. Additional welfare support is also provided by the third sector in the form of Service charities and benevolent organisations. Some welfare support is provided by the Department through its Veteran UK organisation.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130738/answer",,,,,"261532","2019-06-12T15:36:28.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130738/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1130738/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-06-07","Veterans: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of total spending on veterans' support services in (a) Barnsley, (b) South Yorkshire and (c) the UK in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","261533"
